(75, 'UC Berkeley partners with Companies to set up $24M Innovation and Design Institute\n\n', '', 'UC Berkeley’s College of Engineering opened the new Jacob Institute for Design Innovation wherein Bay Area companies will mentor and mold the newest talent coming out of the UC system. The Institute built with an investment of near to $25M contributed by companies such Qualcomm Inc., National Instruments, Autodesk and General Motors is aimed to have companies mentor students and help the next generation innovators build some of those visions or dreams into innovative ventures.&nbsp;<div><br></div><div>The launch of the initiative is backed with the vision of increased emphasis on entrepreneurship and business partnerships supported by some of the leading payers in the valley. It''s a boost to graduates to be successful and create startups that in turn would potentially use Qualcomm and other companies services / offerings for the ventures.\n\n</div>', '14422653351442265799.png', '', '', 0, 2, 0.7374517374517374),
(76, 'Citi Mobile Challenge – 8-10 weeks accelerator program launched in Bangalore', '', 'The Citi Mobile Challenge is a Citi Corporate Accelerator Program for the Asia Pacific Region. It''s, 8-10 week duration and aims to actively network with the startups from countries like India. It''s a combine of virtual Hackathon with an incubator inviting developers from pan India to participate.  The objective is to address proactively the disruption from payment banks, mobile wallets, new age financial technology startups and crypto currencies such as Bitcoin.  \n\nIBM, Google, NASSCOM 10,000 startup program, Amazon, Microsoft Ventures, Wipro and PwC the Bank are partners for the initiative to help Citi select Startups in ecommerce and payments segment.\n\n', '14422655531442265835.png', '', '', 0, 2, 0.7374517374517374),
(77, 'Pixel2desk makes 3D printing easily possible for all in India \n', '', 'Founded by Madhan R, an MS from Cardiff University, UK Pixel2Desk, is 3D printing marketplace wherein one can order customized 3D printed parts or figurines, buy sell 3D printable models, designed by artists from across the globe. Also facilitates those who want to design, own one off models or one of prints.  Initiatives such as free to attend Market fest by the Startup aims to cultivate a community of makers and inventors facilitating a direct interface / guidance by the designers and provides unrestricted access to 3D printers. Pixel2desk caters to B2B segment too–industrial and private R&amp;D projects in areas such as healthcare, automobile etc.<br>‌&nbsp;<br>In short span of 8-10 months, the company has helped Startups like – Mango to prototype its computing product cases; Gyannext in creating customized USB devices, quadcopter canopy for Bangalore based hobbyist etc.  Continuous R&amp;D for technology enhancement is the core, such as the ongoing experiment for a low cost solution to provide 3D scanning services to engineering business and customized jewelry and virtual clothing try-on.  With a team of 6 and initial seed investment by a friend cum mentor, Pixl2desk aims to emerge as the undisputed innovative leader in the 3D printing space in the Asian market.<br>‌&nbsp;<br><b>‌The Founder, Mr. Madhan R said</b>,  “we are in talks with our investors to open hands on experience center in Coimbatore wherein customers will be able to walk-in, touch &amp; feel 3D printed objects, maybe place an order for a 3D printed shoe for themselves or sit down for a product design brainstorming session over a cup of coffee! A 3D printed inmoov robot (http://inmoov.fr/) is also planned for our marketing stunt so watch out if you see one walk around Coimbatore for this New Year”.<br>‌&nbsp;<br><b>NewzByte Interview with the Founder Mr. Madhan R.</b><br>‌&nbsp;<br>‌&nbsp;<br><b>What is the marker size of 3D printing Industry and its potential market?</b><br>The $20 Billion 3D printing industry is set to explode – actually quadruple by 2020. Industrial 3D printing has been happening since yesterday and consumer 3D printing is happening today! Manufacturers are investing heavily in 3D printing technology primarily for Prototyping, Product development, &amp; rapid innovation (creating new products that cannot be created using tradition manufacturing techniques) \n	Don’t be surprised if the spare part you ordered for your washing machine was not shipped but emailed as a digital model by your manufacturer.<br>‌&nbsp;<br>‌<b>What is the winning edge for Pixel2desk in the business arena?</b><br>‌We have passionate people who know their stuff. Our Print quality and subject matter expertise gives us a winning edge over our competitors. We don’t just print we are makers ourselves.  \nWe have the widest choice of 3D printable materials which includes ABS (high strength parts), PLA (bio degradable plastic), Nylon, ninja-flex (flexible sleeves, wearable’s, fabric etc), Faux-wood (40% wood and 60% PLA for decoratives) PET-Glass (for transparent objects) and brushed aluminium.  We focus on really smooth customer experience by being available and providing really fast turnaround time, which our customers love. \n\n	Though our Marketplace division is focused more towards casual end users or for people in the 3D modeling industry who like to share or buy/sell digital models, the real fun is with the bespoke offering that we provide for B2C and B2B customer segment.  \n\nIf you have a product design in mind, say, to invent a new type of shoe and haven’t gotten really anywhere with just the sketches, pixel2desk can help you design it, model it into a 3D model, prototype it fast and iterate. If the tangible prototype meets expectations, pixel2desk can help the makers take it to mass production thanks to our close ties with manufacturers in China who undertake mass manufacturing orders with less than 500 pieces or so quantities via us. \n\n	The other worthy mention is the technology backend that makes ordering 3D prints a seamless experience. Calculation of estimated price, material selection and sizing happens on the fly via an interactive front end, of course it is moderated by a human EOD. \n\n3D printing space in India is rather distributed and disconnected market. As early pioneers within the 3D printing space of India, Pixel2desk makes it a priority to connect the 3D printing space to facilitate seamless accessibility to this technology for the masses. Think of us as Amazon or Flipkart for the 3D printing space – We do maintain part of inventory and operation in-house whereas a part of the orders are processed through our connected print partners throughout India - Very little to zero companies are doing this at the moment.<br>‌&nbsp;<br><b>Profitability and revenue of the company  / Targets set to make it profitable</b><br>‌We have been processing orders via a concierge model since the last 4 months and we have only made just enough to self-sustain the startup. We aim to go official and operate at full capacity by end of October.  We are targeting few niche industries after successfully validating the product: market fit. We will be reaching out to 3D printer owners in the forthcoming weeks to join our print partner programs.  We have set a goal to make the autonomous web service of pixel2desk and bespoke offerings operate at full capacity by end of this year. Would you believe – we have only begun marketing activities few weeks ago only. \n\nIn case you wish to touch base with pixel2desk, please write to madz@pixel2desk.com', '14422661421442266545.jpg', '', '', 0, 2, 0.75),
(78, 'QUBEX is Startup incubator cum accelerator', '', 'QUBEX launched by Nebula Tech Solutions is all about mentoring, an incubator cum accelerator. The initiative is conceptualized with the understanding that mentorship is a continuous process and not limited to few days or months. The mandate is to facilitate in creating business processes and leadership to help drive growth from within the organization.<br>‌&nbsp;<br>‌The focus is to maximize the success potential of Startups and get best results from their ideas. QUBEX business model is a mix of equity and consultation fees, which is linked to the scope of service and level of engagement required by the startup.<br>‌&nbsp;<br>Business Plan, Revenue models, Product development, Launch plan and Marketing strategy is part of the mentorship program and customized as per the requirements.<br>‌&nbsp;<br>QUBEX gets the added advantage of leveraging the extensive business knowledge and resource pool of the organization consisting of senior professionals across business functions to invest their time and learning’s to create value including in the area of digital marketing, enterprise mobility, custom app development and ecommerce business set up.  ', '14422664891442266826.png', '', '', 0, 2, 1),
(82, '<span id="docs-internal-guid-0f0d213f-cdea-9c01-4fda-dfcaa3bc4ad5"><span style="font-size: 16px; font-family: Calibri; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap; background-color: transparent;"> Pentagon funding a new project to develop flexible sensors</span></span>', '', '<span id="docs-internal-guid-0f0d213f-cdea-cf7a-446a-f494e42eb379"><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.2;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;"><span style="font-size: 16px; font-family: Calibri; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap; background-color: transparent;">Defense Secretary Ash Carter has announced that the Pentagon is funding a new venture to develop flexible sensors that can be built into clothing or the skins of ships and aircraft. The technology could be used to develop wearable health monitors that could be built into clothing. </span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.2;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;"><span style="font-size: 16px; font-family: Calibri; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap; background-color: transparent;"><br></span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.2;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;"><span style="font-size: 16px; font-family: Calibri; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap; background-color: transparent;">Carter states that the new technology has enormous potential for the military. It can be used to detect and trigger repair alerts in building and give wounded soldiers smart prosthetics. It could also be used to improve diagnostic X-rays to make breast cancer tests less painful and could be even used to assist the elderly.</span></p><div><span style="font-size: 16px; font-family: Calibri; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap; background-color: transparent;"><span id="docs-internal-guid-0f0d213f-cdea-f492-f1e1-96ad1b1c3cda"><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.2;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); vertical-align: baseline; background-color: transparent;">"Given what we''ve already done, there''s truly no limit to what we can achieve together," said Carter. "That''s why I''ve been pushing the Pentagon to think outside our five-sided box, and invest in innovation here in Silicon Valley and in tech communities across the country."</span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.2;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); vertical-align: baseline; background-color: transparent;"><br></span></p><span style="vertical-align: baseline; background-color: transparent;">The syndicate called the Flexible Hybrid Electronic Institute, will be led by California-based FlexTech Alliance and includes 162 companies, universities and other groups like Apple, HP and United Technologies. Pentagon will provide $75 million for the project while the industry, academia and local government will contribute $96 million over the next five years to create the innovation institute. </span></span><br></span></div></span>', '14422684161442268753.jpeg', '', '', 0, 2, 0.6666666666666666),
(84, 'How much online shoppers around the world are spending', '', 'Over the past few years, online shopping has become increasingly popular around the world. In markets such as the United Kingdom, Japan and Germany, e-commerce penetration has already climbed past 70% of the adult population, and emerging markets such as Brazil and China are seeing rapid growth in online shopping adoption.&nbsp;<div><br>‌But how much are people around the world actually spending online?&nbsp;According to Statista''s Digital Market Outlook, the United States is not only leading in terms of total e-commerce revenue, but also among the countries with the highest revenue per online shopper. On average, Americans are expected to spend $1,804 online this year, almost double of what Japanese shoppers are spending online. </div>', '14422712431442271685.jpg', '', '', 0, 2, 0.6527196652719666),
(85, 'Steve Jobs Got It Wrong, Apple Figures Out Now&nbsp;ǃ', '', 'Apple has launched the iPad Pro and just admitted Bill Gates was right and Steve Jobs was wrong. Years ago Steve Jobs went on about how the early Windows tablet, which was designed for work and had a stylus, was stupid. Steve was not a fan and pretty much dissed the entire tablet idea and then again dissed the whole idea of a stylus when he launched the iPhone.&nbsp;<div><br>‌Tim Cook effectively gave Jobs a royal&nbsp;raspberry with the iPad Pro, which is basically the Apple version of the Windows tablet. The thing is, though, that given the iPod evolved into a small tablet, the iPhone is basically a small tablet with phone capability, and the iPad, well it is the quintessential tablet. Apple has been throwing Jobs'' initial position, that tablets were stupid, into the dumpster for some time now.&nbsp;</div><div><br>‌The&nbsp;thing is, in developing the initial Windows tablet, Microsoft simply didn''t get what users wanted in a tablet very well. Apple''s success was based on better user focus, but Microsoft''s success with Surface Pro indicated there was an important part of the tablet opportunity that Apple was missing -- and Apple just jumped on that. In the end, this could make both companies'' offerings far better over time.</div>', '14422723271442272679.jpg', '', '', 0, 2, 0.5666666666666667),
(87, '3251 App in 30 min and 4000+ drawings in 5 minutes @ KIC Coimbatore  ', '', 'Celebrating the 48th Engineers Day on September 15th, two events Developers 2015 – where 3251 Android Apps for the smart phones developed in 30 minutes and Coloring the Dreams on the theme of Vision 2020 organized by the Karpagam Innovation Centre (KIC) of Karpagam College of Engineering, Coimbatore.\n‌&nbsp;<br>‌<br>‌Termed as YES YOU CAN, the Android App event is a Limca Book of Records attempt by close to 3500 Engineering Students happening for the first time globally. Like wise Coloring the Dreams is about 4000+ Drawings about Vision20/20 within 5 minutes.\n‌&nbsp;<br>‌<br>Dr. B.Nagaraj, Head of Karpagam Innovation Centre and the Principal, Vice-Principal, Dean, Directors, all the Head of Departments, Controller of Examination came out in all support and gave all guidance to make the event a huge success.\n‌<br>‌<br>‌Through these events students will be given a message to strive for excellence in technological innovation taking inspiration from Bharat Ratna Sir Visvesvaraya to make India self reliant and technologically advanced.', '14425762041442576441.jpg', '', '', 0, 2, 0.6666666666666666),
(89, 'Indian origin researcher invents Foldascope-a folding paper microscope ', '', 'Indian origin researcher, Manu Prakash, of Stanford University has invented a new folding paper microscope that costs less than a dollar to manufacture. The microscope dubbed ''Foldascope'' is printed on a thick paper and can be assembled in origami-style in just a few minutes. Prakash states that the paper, lens and other parts of the microscope cost just 50 cents.&nbsp;<br>‌<br>Last year, Prakash and his team had distributed 10,000 Foldscopes to users willing to test them. Many users have been submitting their findings at the Foldscope site, from first-graders looking at banana seeds to investigating tiny insects and more.<br>‌&nbsp;<br>‌Entomologist and science reporter Aaron Pomerantz tested the foldascope in the Peruvian Amazon rainforest and stated in a post, "Long story short, this device is amazing". He adds, "I was able to investigate tiny insects, mites, fungi and plant cells from 140X (magnification) to 480X."<br>‌&nbsp;<br>Prakash says that Foldscope will be able to help health care workers detect blood-borne illnesses in the field. He stated in a Stanford blog post, "I wanted to make the best possible disease-detection instrument that we could almost distribute for free. What came out of this project is what we call use-and-throw microscopy." Although the Foldacope is not commercially available yet, Prakash and has team state that they are "working hard to make the microscopes commercially available via a spinoff/startup."', '14425769511442577213.jpg', '', '', 0, 2, 0.5631578947368421),
(90, 'Samsung Global Innovation Center (GIC) to incubate and invest in Startups in SV', '', 'The Samsung GIC focuses on startups in innovation in areas such as digital health, big data, IOT, Security, Artificial Intelligence, virtual reality, augmented reality and connected car. As strategic investors, Samsung investment is in early stage startups having the potential for strategic partnership with Samsung business units and investment ranges from $250,000 to $3M in Seed, Series A, and Series B rounds.<br>‌&nbsp;<br>‌With close to 30 investments done from 2012 to date, the key mandate of the GIC, other than positive financial returns is the impact the investment has done to Samsung core businesses and value to Startups as an early stage investor like the integration of Pixie, a Smart TV publishing platform into Samsung flagship TVs. SmartThings (IOT and smart home technology) acquired by GIC or in investments in LoopPay (into mobile payments -now Samsung Pay) that today are central to Samsung products roadmap is what GIC is aiming for.', '14425771161442577443.jpg', '', '', 0, 2, 0.9263157894736842),
(91, 'Lasers a danger to self drive cars', '', 'Security researchers have warned that a modified, low-cost laser could create ghostlike objects in the path of autonomous cars, making them slow down and stop completely.<br>‌&nbsp;<br>Jonathan Petit, principal scientist at software company Security Innovation, demonstrated that by using a simple laser pen and a pulse generator, anyone could create phantom objects like cars, buildings, people etc. and stop the self driven cars. The homemade device costs just $40 to make.<br>‌&nbsp;<br>‌Self-driving vehicles come with a LIDAR system to detect potential roadblocks. These LADAR systems use lasers, mounted on top of the cars to detect what''s nearby. Researchers state that by sending false data to the system, anyone can confuse the cars and stop them. Petit says that this type of vulnerability should be a sort of wake-up call to self-driving carmakers.<br>‌&nbsp;<br>"If a self-driving car has poor inputs, it will make poor driving decisions. I can spoof thousands of objects and basically carry out a denial of service attack on the tracking system so it''s not able to track real objects." Petit told IEEE Spectrum. "I can take echoes of a fake car and put them at any location I want," he added.<br>‌&nbsp;<br>Jonathan Petit had written the paper while he was a research fellow at the University of Cork''s computer security group. He will be presenting the findings at the upcoming Black Hat Europe conference in November.', '14426629321442663260.jpg', '', '', 0, 2, 0.6684210526315789),
(92, '''The Travelling Boutique'' will make your trip memorable', '', 'The Travelling Boutique (TTB) is a one-stop shop for travelers and aims to provide a unique retail experience with merchandise that meets customers, every travel need. It offers a diverse range of products, for all travelers, whether you want to go for a business trip or a family vacation or just a trip with friends, TTB has something for you.<br>‌&nbsp;<br>‌The Travelling Boutique, started in February 2015 by two friends Paran Sheth and Pooja Parikh. Since its launch TTB has already completed more than 100 retail and corporate orders. The company plans to diversify into children as well as luxury sectors in the next few months. Also expand and manufacture its own products.<br>‌&nbsp;<br>With the massive growth in the Indian travel industry, TTP has a huge potential. According to a recent report, the travel and tourism sector will contribute Rs. 8.22 trillion to GDP and 37.4 million jobs by 2015 end. The growth is driven by visa reforms, and infrastructure improvements under the new government. More and more travelers are utilizing budget deals, airfare sales etc. to travel.<br>‌&nbsp;<br>‌The company says, "Our aim is to find and give a traveler everything he/she would need to make their travels smooth. That’s where our journey began to become a holistic market place that covers brands, price points and categories of travel accessories that any globetrotter would require. Not quite there yet, but definitely on our way! We want to be every traveler''s online travel accessory store".', '14426632851442663739.png', '', '', 0, 2, 0.5894736842105263),
(93, '''BookMyForex'' meets all your forex needs', '', 'The Indian travel industry is booming due to relaxed visa norms as well as infrastructure improvements. Many financial institutes, banks and money exchanges have started offering deals on foreign currency to aid the growing travel industry. An online forex marketplace like BookyMyForex offers a lot of transparency and competitive pricing for travelers.<br>‌<br>‌BookMyForex is the world''s first and largest online marketplace for buying, selling &amp; remitting forex. Earlier buying forex was very cumbersome and one had to haggle for rates with multiple vendors, BookMyForex provides a single platform where you can get real time quotations on foreign exchange and value for money deals.<br>‌<br>‌The online forex marketplace has tie-ups with leading banks and reputed money exchangers. It has unique features like ''Freeze my rate'' where you can book your forex rate, by paying 2% of the amount upfront. You can also choose ''No Obligation'' orders, which are available 24*7 without any payment and can be cancelled anytime. The company provides forex doorstep delivery in 155 cities or you can choose to pick up your currency from its 4000+ channel partners in 175 cities.<br>‌<br>‌BookMyForex is offering Zero Margin deals on Sept 22, where you will be able exchange foreign currency for free. It also has special discounts for students, combo offers and loyalty programs.', '14428560381442856528.jpg', '', '', 0, 2, 0.5),
(94, 'Eko stethoscope could reinvent healthcare', '', 'Eko Devices, a Silicon Valley startup by three UC Berkeley alumni, has invented a new digital stethoscope that allows doctors to record and share the sound of a patient’s heart. Eko Core has been developed by Connor Landgraf in collaboration with his former classmates Jason Bellet and Tyler Crouch.<br>‌<br>‌Eko Core allows physicians/ medicine practitioners to share recordings of their patient’s heartbeats using an iPhone app with specialists who may be better able to recognize and diagnose abnormalities. The digital stethoscope that’s connected to the Internet will allow a cardiologist to sit in their office and review heart sounds sent from around the world. The device will be extremely beneficial to patients in developing countries as well as in remote areas. Eko is running its pilot project in Stanford Hospital.‌&nbsp;<br><br>‌Jason Bellet, the chief operating officer at Eko Devices stated, “If we can bring expert cardiologists from Johns Hopkins to a patient in rural Nebraska or a rural village in India, that opens up the opportunity to save lives. What we’re seeing with the age of telemedicine is that now we can take a heart sound from a rural, underserved community and send that to a cardiologist for an instant second opinion.”<br>‌&nbsp;<br>‌Eko''s attachment for analog stethoscopes is priced at $199, while a version that filters out ambient noise and allows physicians to focus on the sound of the heart is available for $299.', '14428568381442857113.jpg', '', '', 0, 2, 0.5633333333333334),
(95, 'Emerging markets Impact on App Ecosystem', '', 'According to a report from App Annie, emerging markets like Indonesia, Brazil, India, and Mexico have seen a massive growth in downloads and revenue and provide an unparalleled opportunity for app developers. The report is based on market-level app store growth for iOS and Google Play stores.<br>‌<br>The App Annie report reveals that in Q1, 2015; iOS is ahead Google Play in revenue, however Google Play has seen more downloads. Google Play’s worldwide downloads were 70% higher than the iOS App Store in Q1,2015 and up from 60% in Q3 2014. The main drivers behind Google Play''s growth are emerging markets like Mexico, India, Russia, Indonesia and Brazil. The increase is attributed to first time smartphone users in the emerging countries and the launch of Google''s Android One initiative.<br>‌&nbsp;<br>iOS App Store’s worldwide revenue was 70% higher than Google Play, up from about 60% in Q3 2014. iOS main revenue can be attributed from Apple’s core markets China and US. China has surpassed US in the number of downloads in Q1, 2015. The main reason for the increase in revenue was the launch of Apple''s flagship iPhone 6 and iPhone 6 Plus smartphones. Check out the complete report from App Annie.', '14428571671442857602.png', '', '', 0, 2, 0.4700460829493088),
(96, 'Online food startup ''Baba Fattoosh'' brings ''Ma ka khana to you''', '', 'Craving for some home cooked food? Online food tech startup ''Baba Fattoosh'' brings to you home cooked healthy food that can be eaten everyday.<br>‌&nbsp;<br>‌Founded in 2015 by Devesh Varshney, Baba Fattoosh offers food that is cooked in-house without the use of preservatives or MSG. It offers a new menu to its customers every day, so they don''t get bored. The start-up has a 21-member team and receives over 100 orders every day. Currently the company offers food delivery in East of Bangalore covering tech parks in the areas of Whitefield, ITPL, EPIP, Brookfield, Marathalli, Bellandur etc and plans to expand its operations to cover commercial pockets of Bangalore by Mar-2016.<br>‌&nbsp;<br>‌Devesh Varshney says that the company aims to build a nurturing ecosystem for young working adults to develop healthier lifestyle habits by providing food, tech and personalized support. The venture is also working on a technology module that will track customers food intake habits and chart a healthy and balanced food plan for them accordingly.<br>‌&nbsp;<br>Food Tech touted as a $50 billion market, is expected to grow at close to 150 times in the next few years. According to reports the industry has seen an astounding growth of 16% - 20% y-o-y. In the first half of 2015, the food tech industry has seen over $3.5 billion in investments across 380 disclosed deals, making it the next big thing.', '14428573971442857835.png', '', '', 0, 2, 0.9354166666666667),
(97, 'SmartPlate helps track calories you eat', '', 'Anthony Ortiz, the CEO and founder of Fitly has launched a smartplate for fitness conscious consumers, which can track the number of calories the eat. The smartplate uses food recognition technology that tells you the nutritional value of a meal, as well as the complete break down of the number of carbs, proteins and fats that you have eaten.<br>‌&nbsp;<br>‌The SmartPlate has three digital cameras, which photograph the food on the plate and then transfer the photos via WiFi to a mobile device. The images of the food are then compared to the database of images on the internet, to help classify the food items on the plate.<br>‌<br>‌Ortiz says that SmartPlate''s proprietary algorithms identifies foods in less than a second. "SmartPlate is the most intelligent plate on the planet," Ortiz says. "Using digital cameras and weight sensors, it instantly tracks and analyzes everything a consumer eats with up to 99.7 percent accuracy." She added that, "Currently, our technology can identify things like mixed salads, rice pilaf, spaghetti with meatballs and turkey wraps."<br>‌<br>‌The company aims to raise awareness on nutrition and healthy eating and has teamed up with the American Heart Association. SmartPlate will be donating 1 percent of their revenues to the cause, "our hope is more people will learn how to use accountability tools like SmartPlate," Ortiz stated.', '14428577661442858172.jpeg', '', '', 0, 2, 0.51),
(98, 'Biometrics startup Tascent raises $18.5 Mln in Series A funding', '', 'Global biometrics startup Tascent has raised $18.5 million in Series A funding led by Tano Capital to develop its iris recognition systems for airport and high-level security. The company has already introduced its systems at the Dubai International Airport, London Gatwick Airport as well as a number of high-security facilities in the US.<br>‌<br>‌Founded in 2015 by Dean Senner, the biometrics uses Iris scanning technology to provide additional and efficient security. Global healthcare biometrics revenue is expected to reach $3.5 billion by 2024, with the additional funding the company aims to grow its product line in government, enterprise and other market sectors. The company which already has offices in Singapore, Dubai and Washington, D.C, plans to expand its presence globally.<br>‌&nbsp;<br>‌Senner stated in a press release announcing the funding round, "Over the past few years, biometrics has become a positive and impactful aspect of our daily lives. We’re excited to build upon this momentum with highly accurate and easy-to-use identity solutions that contribute to a safer and more efficient world.” He added, “Our strength in iris recognition, along with products that embrace multiple biometric modalities including fingerprint and face recognition, empowers us to deliver flexible and customizable solutions to customers globally.”', '14428582871442858779.jpg', '', '', 0, 2, 0.7152173913043478),
(99, 'Vzibl’, a marketing tool for SMB marketers by Datawrkz', '', 'Advertising technology provider Dataworkz recently launched a platform- Vizibl. It aims at making programmatic advertising accessible to SMB agencies and brands.<br> <br>\nSenthil Govindan, CEO and Anand Prakash, COO, Datawrkz founded Vizibl specifically for the mid-market advertising segment. The Pay-as-you-go demand side platform provides the best technology for SMB marketers to launch large-scale advertising campaigns.<br>‌&nbsp;<br>The automated platform analyses multiple variables in real time, to make sure that Advertisers get the right campaign. The tool does not require a minimum spend or any upfront costs, and advertisers have the freedom to define their own budgets, goals and attribution model.<br>‌&nbsp;<br>‌Key USP of Vizibl in the advertising domain:<br>\n1. Programmatic advertising, democratic and accessible to agencies and brands of all sizes<br>\n2. Advertisers get complete control and transparencies over the respective campaigns<br>\n3. No commitment towards a minimum monthly spend<br>\n4. Provides advertisers access to the largest programmatic exchanges in the world no matter what their ad budget is<br>\n5. Specifically beneficial for the mid and small size advertisers<div><br>\nThe Founders and the core team intends to make tools such as contextual targeting, fraud detection and dynamic creative optimization available through Vizibl, in the near future, in order to ensure that clients are able to access the same kind of full ad technology stack available as available to large agencies and clients.</div>', '14428585301442858773.jpg', '', '', 0, 2, 1),
(101, 'FLUID- A smart water meter for your home', '', 'FLUID is a new smart water meter that helps you in conserving water by detecting usage and leaks to save money. Launched on Kickstarter, Fluid water meter connects via Wi-Fi and gives you real-time reports of water usage on your iPhone or Android device.<br>\n <br>\nFLUID helps you understand exactly when, where and how much water you’re consuming in your home on a daily basis. The device easily snaps on to your water pipe, and sends notifications if it detects possible leaks or running water in your home. The smart meter creates signatures which help in identifying water usage by each appliance or fixture in your home. So you will be able to monitor how much water you''re using for things like dishwashing, showers, laundry, flushes, lawn irrigation, etc. Going forward the technology will also be integrated with smart home monitors like Nest or SmartThings, and will provide a REST API so developers can build their own integrations.<br>\n <br>\nFLUID co-founder Josh Becerra says, “Right now consumers get a water bill every month and it’s in units, not gallons, so you have to flip the sheet over and do some math to find out how many gallons you’re using. FLUID is really about empowering consumers to take more control over their water usage.”', '14431003591443100479.png', '', '', 0, 2, 0.75),
(102, 'Symantec warns about dangers of IoT, Wearbles', '', 'Security provider Symantec has issued a warning about IoT and smart devices being vulnerable to cyber criminals. According to a report, hackers have started breaching smart devices and more cases of ransomware are surfacing online.<br>\n <br>\nMcAfee Labs reported that the number of ransomware samples identified grew 127 percent from Q2 2014 to Q2 2015. The company says that security in IoT devices is still very unsophisticated, making it easy for cybercriminals to hack the systems and hold them for Ransomware.<br>\n <br>\nThe researchers demonstrated the threat by infecting a Moto 360 smartwatch with the Android Simplocker ransomware, causing the smartwatch to become unusable. Smartwatches are not the only thing vulnerable, Symantec researcher Candid Wueest stated that, "It''s very plausible that we''ll see ransomware on smart TVs, routers or any other smart devices in the future." She added that an infected smartphone could scan its owner''s home network for vulnerable devices and infect those found with malicious code.<br>\n <br>\nSymantec has advised users against installing apps on their smart devices from unknown or un-trusted sources to prevent hacking. The security firm states that users should check permissions when installing apps to make sure they''re appropriate. Users should also make sure that security software on their mobile devices is up to date.', '14431005141443100845.jpg', '', '', 0, 2, 1),
(104, 'Gapoon makes Home Maintenance comfortable and easy! ', '', 'Gapoon is a Bangalore based startup that provides a one-stop solution for all your home maintenance needs. The company has a free Android app that allows you to hire servicemen with just a click of a button and facilitates checkout in just 3 seconds!<br>\n<br>\nStarted by three IIT Kanpur Alumnus Ankita Asai, Apoorva Mishra and Ankit Bindal in Feb, 2015, Gapoon allows you to hire verified professionals for home maintenance including plumbers, electricians, pest control, carpenters, painters, house-cleaners, laptop &amp; appliance repairmen. The site mentions the prices of the services upfront and has a fully automated lead management system with end-to-end follow-up on every lead. Gapoon successfully connects a customer with his best-suited vendor based on <br>\nattribute mapping &amp; location within 15 minutes. <br>\n<br>\nSince its launch, Gapoon has over 2000 satisfied customers, and has shown a 50% monthly growth rate in terms of daily visitors, queries and completed orders. The company has seen a zero attrition rate from vendors and has a high number of repeat customers. The Chief Marketing officer and Founder, Ms. Ankita Asai shared to Newsbyte that Gapoon has been able to ensure these qualities because of its seamless operational management &amp; tech edge. When asked about the key areas wherein the Startup faced challenges, the team was very categorical in stating that Gapoon has faced multiple challenges, such as:<br>\n	•	Limited resources as a seed funded startup<br>\n	•	Tough competition in the market <br>\n	•	Training of vendors and <br>\n	•	Geographical expansion<br>\n<br>\nHome maintenance is the largest disorganized sector in the country, with an opportunity of billion jobs. The market leaders in the sector have captured only 1-1.5% of it, leaving a lot of scope for expansion. Currently only in Bangalore, Gapoon aims to establish a pan-India presence and expand to 14 other major cities by 2016.<br>\n<br>\nAnkita Asai, Gapoon''s CMO and founder gives three takeaways for aspiring entrepreneurs, "I would say that in the world-up of start-ups perseverance takes one a long way. It is all about the ''not giving up attitude'' that will guarantee you success. As an entrepreneur, have a long term vision for your company and align your team members to share that common vision. Until you think big, you won''t make big".', '14431017071443102156.png', '', '', 0, 2, 0.3888048411497731),
(105, 'Smartphones driving India’s e-commerce industry', '', 'India will surpass US to become the second biggest smartphone nation with over 500 million mobile internet users by 2017. According to a recent report, by 2016 the country will have over 236 million mobile internet users, and will cross 314 million milestone by 2017.<br>‌&nbsp;<br>Smartphone shipments in Q2 2015 have reached 26.5 million units, up by 44% of the Q2 2014. With the launch of more budget devices, India will see a double-digit growth in smartphone sales to become the second biggest smartphone nation after China. The increased penetration of smartphones is the major driving force of growth in the e-commerce sector. According to a recent report, the e-commerce segment in India will grow from $1.7 billion in 2015 to $2.3 billion by 2017. Most of the online traffic to eCommerce sites in India is coming from mobiles. ', '14431814821443181778.jpg', '', '', 0, 2, 0.6451612903225806),
(106, '', '', '<p style="margin-bottom: 0px; font-size: 12px; line-height: normal; font-family: Helvetica;">According to reports, Amazon''s 50% of the traffic is coming through mobile devices, while e-commerce giant Flipkart receives 70-75% traffic from mobile app alone and Snapdeal’s 75% sales are from smartphones. Online wallet PayTm has revealed that 80% of its business order is sourced through mobiles. The companies expect that over the next 3 years 90% of their traffic will come from smartphones.</p>', '14431815561443181678.jpg', '', '', 105, 1, 0.7705078125),
(107, '4D Printing technology can create self-folding objects', '', 'Researchers from Georgia Institute of Technology and Singapore University of Technology and Design, have developed a new 4D printing technology that could be used to create 3D structures that fold themselves from smart memory shape-memory polymers that had been flat or rolled into a tube for shipment. <br>\n<br>\nThe components would respond to a single source of stimulation in a precise and timely movements, causing the flat object to respond to create new 3D structures without the various parts colliding. To simplify the tech, the researchers used a uniform temperature application technique to internally control their rate of shape change through their molecular design. <br>\n<br>\nThe researchers stated, “An important aspect of self-folding is the management of self-collisions, where different portions of the folding structure contact and then block further folding. A metric is developed to predict collisions and is used together with the reduced-order model to design self-folding structures that lock themselves into stable desired configurations.” <br>\n<br>\nThe team suggested that the components will be able to respond to stimuli like heat, moisture or light and have various applications in space structures, robots, deployable medical devices, toys, etc. The technology could be applied to something as complex as an unmanned air vehicle, which will maintain a different configuration while cruising altitude and then abruptly shift into a second configuration for landing or diving. The findings were published in the journal Scientific Reports.', '14442892561444289568.jpg', '', '', 0, 2, 0.6666666666666666),
(108, 'Microsoft launches Rare Replay collection of 30 Classic games', '', 'Microsoft on Tuesday launched the Rare Replay collection, a compilation of 30 best games in Xbox History. The collection was announced at the 2015 Electronic Entertainment Expo and released worldwide as an Xbox One exclusive. Launched at $30 Rare Replay includes games like Perfect Dark, Blast Corps, Battletoads, as well as retro classics like Snake Rattle N'' Roll. <br>\n<br>\nRare Replay spans games across multiple genres and consoles, ranging from the ZX Spectrum to the Xbox 360 and come with the some features as their original releases. Microsoft announced the collection at its Gamescom event in Germany which focused largely on the exclusive games coming to the Xbox One this year and in 2016. Xbox exclusives slated to arrive later this year include Lara Craft- Rise of the Tomb Raider, sci-fi shooter Halo 5 Guardians and Forza Motorsport 6. The 2016 Xbox releases include Recore and Sea of Thieves, Quantum Break, Crackdown 3 and Scalebound.<br>\n<br>\nXbox Chief Phil Spencer stated at the launch, "That vision includes the games you want to play, and the connection to the people you want to play with, across the devices you want to play on. Whether you''re a console gamer, a PC gamer or both, we are committed to delivering the experience you expect from Microsoft."<br>\n', '14442896171444289978.png', '', '', 0, 2, 0.5677966101694916),
(109, '''SafePay'' system to stop credit card fraud ', '', 'Researchers have developed a new method called ''SafePay'' to prevent credit card fraud using magnetic card readers. The system converts disposable credit card information to electrical current, with a magnetic card chip to simulate the behavior of a physical magnetic card. ''SafePay'' will help in thwarting credit card fraud which accounts for approximately $8 billion in incurred losses every year in the U.S alone.<br>\n<br>\nThe system uses a mobile banking application to communicate with bank servers and generates a disposable credit card number which expires after a single transaction. So even if the information is stolen it cannot be used by cyber criminals for future transactions. The magnetic credit card chip is compatible with all existing readers and costs just $0.5. <br>\n<br>\nThe research is being led by Yinzhi Cao assistant professor of computer science and engineering at Lehigh University (Bethlehem, PA) along with coauthors Yan Chen and Xiang Pan from Northwestern University. The team conducted real-world experiments with the ‘SafePay’ technology and all the transactions were successful. Cao and his colleagues will present the research at the IEEE Conference on Communications and Network Security next week in Florence, Italy from September 28-30. <br>\n<br>\nCao stated that, "Because SafePay is backward compatible with existing magnetic card readers, it will greatly relieve the burden of merchants in replacing card readers and at the same time protect cardholders from mass data breaches."<br>\n', '14442923961444292531.jpg', '', '', 0, 2, 0.7658402203856749),
(110, 'Sri Lanka to get Google''s internet powered balloons', '', 'Google has been working on Project Loon to bring internet to remote parts of the world. The internet giant''s Project Loon uses high-altitude balloons attached with a solar panel at an altitude of about 12 miles in the stratosphere to create an aerial wireless network with up to 4G LTE speeds to a 25 mile area. <br>\n<br>\nSri Lanka will be one of the first countries to see project Loon''s balloon-powered Internet. Only 1 in 5 people have access to internet in the country. Google has partnered with local telecommunications companies in Sri Lanka to transmit signal to the balloon network for free. The technology will allow millions of people living in rural areas to get connected to the internet and access social services and education.<br>\n<br>\nSri Lanka with a small population of 22 million and an area of 25,000 square miles that is ideal for a Loon network. If this first deployment goes well, more Loon networks will be launched in other developing countries as well. <br>\n<br>\n"Hopefully in a few months every person and every device on the island will be covered," said Harsha de Silva, Deputy Minister of Policy Planning and Economic Affairs. The connections from the balloons will be "shared, bringing down transmission costs leading to further reductions in cost of service provision," he said.<br>\n', '14442927731444293001.jpg', '', '', 0, 2, 0.5392156862745098);
