(111, 'Top 10 Ranking Start-ups in India', '', 'India is one the fastest growing and the third largest startup ecosystem in the world. According to reports more than 800+ start-ups are being set up annually in the country and by 2020 India will have over 11500 startups employing over 250 K people.<br>\n<br>\nIn the first half of 2015 India has seen investment of $3.5 billion in start-ups in 380 deals, and this scenario is expected to grow in the coming years. Snapshot of the top 10 startups in India as per the site Startup Ranking.<br>\n<br>\nFreshDesk: is a cloud-based customer support platform, that allows organisations to offer customer service support via email, website, social media etc. The company has an easy to use interface, with more than 40,000 customers worldwide.<br>\n<br>\nMyntra:  is one of the biggest online fashion retailer in India with a wide range of products from clothing, accessories to footwear etc. The company was acquired by ecommerce giant flipkart in an estimated Rs 2000 crore deal in 2014.<br>\n<br>\nJabong: Online ecommerce store Jabong offers a wide range of fashion and lifestyle products. The company is valued between $500mln to $800m and offers over 190,000 products from 1,800 brands, ranging from its own labels to well-known international brands.<br>\n<br>\nZomato: Founded in 2008, Zomato is a global restaurant search engine. The company operates in over 22 countries globally and has over 19 million monthly visitors. Zomato has raised over $225 million in funding and is currently valued at over $1 billion.<br>\n<br>\nInfibeam: is an online ecommerce retailer offering over 1.2 Crore products across different categories including books, electronics and lifestyle products. The Ahmedabad based company is looking at a valuation of $1 Billion in its proposed IPO.<br>\n<br>\nHolidayIQ:  is an online holiday information portal powered by user-generated content like reviews, pictures and experiences. The company is valued at $55 million and has over 10 million visitors a month.<br>\n<br>\nBookMyShow: is one of India’s biggest online ticketing site. The company shows details about upcoming movies, events along with show timings, venue details, etc. The site has over 1 billion page views a month, 50 million visits and sells over 6 million tickets a month.<br>\n<br>\nMagzter : is online digital magazine newsstand, offers content from over 2500+ leading publishers and 6000+ magazines. The company has a revenue share model with publishers on magazine sales and has over 26+ million readers.<br>\n<br>\nGoibibo:  is one of the largest online travel aggregator in India, which enables travelers to search, compare and buy air and bus tickets as well as make hotel reservations. The travel aggregator received 465,904 daily page views and has an estimated website traffic worth $1 M in US dollars.<br>\n<br>\nCoupon Duniya : With Times Internet, having acquired a majority stake in Mumbai-based CouponDunia Media Private Limited,  the startup is said to be India’s largest and most popular digital coupon marketplace connecting consumers with retailers and brands. Claims to receive over 2 million+ visits a month and  driving Rs 500 Cr of purchases annually from over 1500 online retailers and brands. The company states its business offering to be a win –win where the customer gets better deals and partner merchants a chance to push their sales and CouponDuniya earning a commission by the partner merchant.', '14443803101444380502.png', '', '', 0, 2, 0.23615635179153094),
(112, '5.6 Million fingerprints stolen by cybercriminals, confirms Office of Personnel Management (OPM), Washington', '', 'The Office of Personnel Management (OPM), Washington has confirmed that hackers have stolen over 5.6 million fingerprints of federal employees in one of the biggest cyber breaches ever. The hackers have also stolen personal information, including address and Social Security numbers of over 21.5 million current and former government employees.<br>\n<br>\nOPM is in the process of notifying everyone affected by the breach. The agency states that it will be providing free identity theft and fraud protection services for the people whose fingerprints were hacked. OPM stated, “If in the future, new means are developed to misuse the fingerprint data, the government will provide additional information to individuals whose fingerprints may have been stolen in this breach.”<br>\n<br>\nAs more smart devices are using biometric sensors like fingerprints for additional security, experts are becoming concerned how cyber criminals may leverage these stolen fingerprints in the future. Theft of biometric data like fingerprints has shook security experts as unlike passwords, fingerprints cannot be changed. Federal experts believe that their is limited potential for “misuse” of the stolen fingerprints as of now, but that could significantly “change over time as technology evolves.”<br>\n<br>\nThe cyber attack on OPM which keeps the US government’s most important personnel records, has been attributed to China by American intelligence agencies, but it remains unclear which group or organization is behind it.', '14443837971444384147.png', '', '', 0, 3, 0.75),
(113, 'Ducere Technologies ‘Lechal’ is the world’s first haptic footwear', '', 'In India, startups are recognizing the opportunity in the sector and wearable tech is expected to become the next big thing. By 2019, India will have an Rs 200 million wearable market. Indian startups have also recently entered the wearable tech industry and are launching new products in the segment.<br>\n<br>\nFounded by Krispian Lawrence and Anirudh Sharma in 2011, Ducere Technologies has created the world’s first haptic footwear that recreates the sense of touch through vibration. The company aims at creating intuitive, unobtrusive and user friendly wearable technology innovations.<br>\n<br>\nHere are the excerpts from an NewzByte interview with the Ducere Technologies team.<br>\n<br>\nQ: What does your company do? Please explain the concept of company/ product?<br>\n<br>\nR: Lechal is the world’s first haptic footwear, and allows hands-free navigation, while tracking your fitness metrics. By pairing with the Lechal app via Bluetooth, users will be able to receive directions via haptic vibrations on their feet. If the wearer needs to turn left, the left side will gently vibrate and so on. Available as an insole or a shoe, the stylish and comfortable smart footwear can be worn like any other, but offers never-before-seen functionality.<br>\n<br>\nThe smart shoes work as a fitness trackers and monitor steps taken, calories burned and distance traveled. Users can also set up fitness goals via the company’s app to track progress and share with friends.<br>\n<br>\nTravelers can discover new destinations and use the smart footwear to tag locations, set destinations and get real-time data on landmarks. Lechal also boasts of unique voice commands and allows you to share your location with other users. The footwear is ideal for groups of families and friends that want to keep track of everyone. For example, if a group is scattered across an amusement park but plans to meet at the same restaurant for dinner, Lechal can provide real-time location data.<br>\n<br>\nQ: What were the challenges and learning in establishing your company?<br>\n<br>\nR: Initially, the biggest challenge was getting people on board, from finding the right talent to finding the right vendors and setting up business partnerships. The R&amp;D phase was a huge learning experience as there aren’t a lot of avenues for innovative product development in India. But over time, as our media profile increased, it helped bringing in more like-minded individuals to us.<br>\n<br>\nQ: Is there any particular TG you follow?<br>\n<br>\nR: Lechal is for everyone – early adopters of wearables, people who like to travel, fitness freaks, runners, design aficionados as well as the fashion-conscious.<br>\n<br>\nQ: Are there any promotional and marketing activities you are doing?<br>\n<br>\nR: Since Lechal has only just hit the market, we will begin a digital marketing campaign shortly. Till date, the focus has been primarily on PR.<br>\n<br>\nQ: What are your expansion plans?<br>\n<br>\nR: Our immediate focus is mass production and distribution of Lechal. We also have other wearable tech products in various stages of development which will enable us to grow a healthy patent portfolio.<br>\n<br>\nQ: What is your business model and the size of your team?<br>\n<br>\nR: We do business in multiple channels – B2C, where we sell directly from our website as well as through distribution partners globally, and B2B, where we partner with organizations that work with the visually-challenged. We have 100 employees and plan to grow considerably in the next few months.', '14443839641444384307.png', '', '', 0, 3, 0.3858695652173913),
(114, 'India gets $30.93 billion in FDI in 2014-15, growth rate revised to 7.4%', '', 'India has received over $30.93 billion in FDI investments in the  fiscal year 2014-15, which is 27% more than last year 2013-14. The Department of Industrial Policy and Planning stated that inflows have jumped by 48% since the launch of PM’s ‘Make in India’ programme in September 2014, compared with an year ago.<br>‌&nbsp;The trade deficit has lowered to $12.5 billion from $12.8 billion in July, primarily because of lower oil imports. In the current financial year, imports have shrunk 11.6% to $168.6 billion and exports have declined 16.2% to $111.1 billion, mainly due to falling global commodity prices and weak domestic demand. The trade deficit has lowered to $12.5 billion from $12.8 billion in July, primarily because of lower oil imports. ', '14443864031444386542.png', '', '', 0, 2, 0.4853801169590643),
(115, '', '', '<span style="font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 15px; line-height: 26.25px;">In the current financial year, imports have shrunk 11.6% to $168.6 billion and exports have declined 16.2% to $111.1 billion, mainly due to falling global commodity prices and weak domestic demand. The trade deficit has lowered to $12.5 billion from $12.8 billion in July, primarily because of lower oil imports. Th</span><strong style="zoom: 1; border: 0px; font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0px; outline: 0px; padding: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; line-height: 26.25px;">e Gross Domestic Product (GDP)</strong><span style="font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 15px; line-height: 26.25px;">&nbsp;in India was 7% in the second quarter of 2015 compared with the Q2,2014. Global investors have sold shares worth approx Rs 22,693 crore in August-September this year amidst concerns of US Federal Reserve increasing interest rates and a slowdown in China.</span>', '14443870061444387379.png', '', '', 114, 1, 0.4574314574314574),
(116, '', '', '', '14443870361444387167.png', '', '', 114, 2, 2.079754601226994),
(117, '', '', '<span style="font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 15px; line-height: 26.25px;">India has seen more interest from foreign investors in 2014-15 financial year and with the continuing reforms the economic growth is expected to surpass last year’s 7.3% by a marginal 7.4%.</span>', '14443870891444387378.png', '', '', 114, 3, 0.4773060029282577),
(119, 'Five promising IOT startups in India', '', 'Internet of Things (IOT) is becoming the next big thing with many VC firms investing in the technology. IOT devices are expected to add $1.7 trillion to the global economy by 2019 and are estimatedFive promising IOT startups in India to be double the size of the smartphone, PC, tablet and wearable market combined.<br>\n<br>\nHere is the list of some disruptive IOT startups in India.<br>\n<br>\nCovacsis Technologies :  is a Mumbai-based startup that designs and implements an intellectual plant framework (IPF) for manufacturing industries. The system can obtain data from any appliance installed on the shop floor and allow real-time view of cost, quality and productivity, thereby making it simpler to track the key performance indicators (KPIs) of the business. The company is backed by Reliance, Cisco and Blume Ventures.<br>\n<br>\nAltimetrik: At the core of Altimetric are the 3 global mega trends of Digital, Connected Solutions &amp; Consumer Technologies, which the company leverages to transform business and offer technology solutions to global enterprise customers. The company uses technology as an enabler to offer consultancy on future trends adoption and a serves as a catalyst to make the transformation smooth.<br>\n<br>\nMachineTalk:  allows customers to transform a traditional product or device into a ‘smart’, connected product.  The Bangalore-based startup offers an IoT Platform that includes a Cloud Gateway, Cloud Storage, Big Data Analytics and Visualization features. To build a hardware-based IoT product, customers can plug and play directly in the platform and accelerate their product development, while for an app for IoT, the platform can be used to incorporate more features into the app by leveraging Big Data Analytics.<br>\n<br>\nToymail: has designed special toys, through which people can send a voice message to their children, parents or just about anyone at anytime and from anywhere they like using the Toymail app. It is a great tool for moms to stay connected with their kids, while at work.<br>\n<br>\nLifePlot:  is an electrocardiography diagnosis tool which records data for a basic medical diagnosis. It is the lightest portable electrocardiography (ECG) machine in the world, ideal for travelers. The device, priced at Rs. 40,000, is being used in over 100 medical institutions in India.', '14443878001444388167.png', '', '', 0, 3, 0.8659966499162479),
(120, 'Sodium-ion batteries can power future technology', '', 'Researchers from Purdue University are looking at Sodium as an alternative to lithium powered batteries to meet future technology needs. The team led by Vilas Pol, an Associate Professor of chemical engineering and doctoral students Arthur Dysart and Jialiang Tang at Purdue, state that there is need for new sodium powered batteries as its,  widely available around the world, while Lithium is available in limited quantities and there will be a lithium shortage in the coming years.<br>\n<br>\nThe team is working on replacing the lithium-ion batteries internal components with running sodium counterparts. The one drawback of the sodium-ion batteries is that they are slightly heavier than lithium-ion batteries. The researchers are trying to improve the sodium-ion batteries by using a wide range of customized carbons and their combinations with sodium-alloying materials such as tin and antimony that could potentially double the capacity of the anodes, making it possible to make smaller anodes and reduce the size and weight of the batteries.<br>\n<br>\nSodium-ion batteries can power future technology“The main advantage of sodium-ion batteries is the potential financial benefit,” Dysart said. “Lithium is a very scarce element in the world. We could actually experience a lithium shortage in coming years. Pol added: “Sodium is more abundant and a thousand times cheaper than lithium. It’s even in seawater.”', '14443880851444388542.png', '', '', 0, 3, 0.6226175349428208),
(121, 'New hybrid solar panel that will reduce your energy bills', '', 'Scientists at Brunel University London have designed a new hybrid roofing system that generates five times more energy by harnessing sunlight and heat at the same time. The new-patented system could reduce energy bills in homes.<br>\n<br>\nFor the new solar panels, scientists used a new conductive polymer known as PEDOT, and added layer of “dye-sensitized solar cell” on top of the PEDOT film. Underneath the panel they added a thin pyroelectric film and thermoelectric device capable of converting the heat energy into electricity.<br>\n<br>\nThe process created a 20 percent higher rate of efficiency compared with commercial solar cells. The patented system employs a unique amalgamation of technologies to pre-heat domestic hot water for radiators, baths and showers while also generating electricity that could light small LED bulbs.<br>\n<br>\nResearchers are doing trials of the new roof at the Building Research Establishment (BRE) in Watford where a prototype is being tested for powering a three-bedroom house.<br>\n<br>\nDr Hussam Jouhara of Brunel Institute of Energy Futures, who led the respective British research team, stated that until now there there is no system which fully addresses all the technical and practical issues thereby making an entire building’s roof a solar-powered generator of both heat energy and electrical energy.”<br>\n<br>\nDr Jouhara,said, “Our solar panels are PV coated for the most southerly-facing aspect of the roof and are designed to clip together as a weather-tight roof as simply as clicking together laminate flooring”. He added, “Our flat heat pipes are so efficient that they can actually capture the energy from early morning dew evaporating off the trial roof.”', '14443882171444388487.png', '', '', 0, 3, 0.5033557046979866),
(122, 'Mobile Internet emerging as a key tool for ecommerce sales in India', '', 'With customer preferences shifting to smartphones, mobile internet is emerging as a key tool for ecommerce sales in India and this is giving a strong push to the already thriving mobile games and apps market, estimated to be worth over Rs 2000 crore by 2016, reported by the recently released ICRIER and IAMAI report.  Added to this, the telecom market predicts the number of 3G sim cards to jump from 35 million in 2012 to 272 million by 2017 – all showing that the trend of Mobile Internet and Apps is surely on the upward trajectory.<br>\n<br>\nIndia sees over 100 million downloads every month even though smartphone penetration is less than 20% in the country. Apart from metros, the growth has been driven by growing demand for smartphones in Tier 2 and Tier 3 cities for affordable yet feature rich devices. This all leads to corroborating the research data that Mobile app usage in India has outpaced global app usage in 2015 and seen a rise of 131%, though app usage in South Asia grew at 77% in the same period. Mobile Internet<br>\n<br>\nIt is also projected that India is expected to have over 382 million smartphone users by 2016 making it the second biggest smartphone nation and contributing significantly to App development since Indians; either based abroad or at home, develop ten per cent of Apps worldwide, the market is yet to be tapped.<br>\n<br>\nThe growing popularity of mobile internet and apps in India is further strengthened by the fact that India is among the top five regions for app downloads on Google Play Store. Users in India download apps in the entertainment category the most, that includes Bollywood, cricket, mobile games, music apps, instant messaging apps and social media apps, followed by online shopping and ecommerce sites. A recent release by MoMagic Technologies, a key player in the mobile internet market offering reach, acquisition and analytical data to startups- leading ecommerce players and partners with some of the key OEMs, reflects similar trends:<br>\n<br>\n15% -18% month on month growth in App Installation<br>\n43% of the app installation in mobiles priced between 5000 to 10,000<br>\n64% installations on TOP 5 Indian-Chinese brands and 36% on Global TOP 5 brands<br>\nTier II Cities showing more appetite for growth and potential of further penetration<br>\nGames, Social Networking, Entertainment are the 3 most in demand APPs in Tier II Cites with Utility catching up fast<br>\nFlipkart, Amazon and PayTm are some of the most downloaded e-commerce apps in India. The apps are helping companies reap the benefits of better customer engagement and help retain customers. The strategic moves by players viz, Flipkart-acquired Myntra having gone app-only in May this year and Flipkart too revealing plans of going app only, stating that 70% of its sales come from mobile and online giant Snapdeal sharing that mobile accounts for 75% of its sales is an endorsement of the trends and potential of mobile internet and apps market in India.<br>\n<br>\nMoMagic Technologies targeting mobile -apps and games to connect with consumers has reached the 90 million users milestone in India in a span of 55 months, which includes 75 million smartphone users through OEMs, 12 million users via OTA (over the air) and 3 million users offline. According to a company release, MoMagic has registered 300% y-o-y growth in revenue for FY 2014-2015.<br>\n<br>\nSeeing the potential, recently the Internet and Mobile Association of India (IAMAI) launched Mobile 10X to nurture and grow the apps ecosystem in India. The forum will set up mobile startup hubs, which will train over 500,000 app developers in the next five years and do online mentoring of app developers, making India the biggest App developer community in the world. This is a part of the of the government’s Digital India initiative, for which Rs.1, 000 crores have been set aside for technology startups in the Union Budget 2015-16. And the race for 4G in the telecom sector has begun, all indicating that mobile internet and app market is in for longer innings!', '14443885971444389053.png', '', '', 0, 1, 1.1111111111111112),
(123, 'Researchers invent self-destructing chips to stop Cyber criminals', '', 'Researchers at Xerox PARC have deResearchers invent self-destructing chips to stop Cybercriminalsveloped new self-destructing microchips that can be embedded on glass. The micro-chips are a part of Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency’s Vanishing Programmable Resources project and can explode on command. The aim of the project is to secure personal data from cyber criminals.<br>\n<br>\nThe exploding glass was demonstrated at DARPA’s event in St. Louis earlier in September. The researchers stated that the microchips can be embedded on a hardened glass surface, which can be used to destroy encryption keys stored on memory chips in electronic devices. The chips are meant to provide an additional layer of protection if a device is stolen and there is a chance of sensitive information being hacked by cyber criminals. By destroying the device, hackers will no longer be able to access the data on the stolen device.<br>\n<br>\nGregory Whiting, project’s lead scientist and his team took strengthened glass and used a process called “ion exchange tempering” to toughen the glass from outside. He added that the explosion can be caused by issuing a variety of commands including a voice, photodiode, a radio signal, a laser, or even a mechanical switch.<br>\n<br>\nWhiting stated that, “The applications we are interested in are data security and things like that. We really wanted to come up with a system that was very rapid and compatible with commercial electronics.”', '14443888841444389160.png', '', '', 0, 1, 0.5578635014836796),
(125, 'Samsung says Startups are its “secret ingredient” for innovation', '', 'Electronics giant Samsung says that startups are the secret ingredient that will help the company innovate. The company is working on “cultivating deep relationships” with startups and startup ecosystems globally.Samsung says Startups are its secret sauce<br>\n<br>\nIn a blog post Samsung said that startups are the “secret ingredient” of its innovation. “To evolve its software and service presence, and continue building compelling consumer experiences, [we are] cultivating deep relationships with startup ecosystems in Silicon Valley, New York City, and around the globe,” the company added. It plans to strengthen its relationships with startup ecosystems by 4 key factors, viz: investments, acquisitions, partnerships and its Accelerator programs in San Francisco and New York.<br>\n<br>\nDavid Eun, Samsung’s EVP, Global Innovation Center (GIC), stated, “By working with startups at any stage of development, GIC engages with entrepreneurs in a variety of ways, offering them more opportunities than investments would alone.”<br>\n<br>\nEarlier this month, the South Korean giant had announced its new SmartThings Hub at IFA in Berlin, which it says is the open ecosystem push into the Internet of Things (IoT). Samsung had purchased SmartThings in a $200 million deal in August last year. The company believes IoT will be its next big driver and says that by 2017, 90% of its products will be able to connect to the web.', '14443891541444389445.jpg', '', '', 0, 3, 0.6666666666666666),
(126, 'Harvard Challenge aimed at improving health care', '', 'Harvard Business School in collaboration with Harvard Medical School had announced the Health Acceleration Challenge, in order to come up with innovative ideas to improve health care delivery. The aim of the challenge was to come up with innovative solutions in the health care industry that can be implemented across geographies as well as care delivery systems that can be put into  practice immediately rather than taking years to establish.<br>\n<br>\nHarvard has announced Bloodbuy, I-PASS, Medalogix and Twine Health as the four finalists in the challenge who will share the prize money of $150,000. Each finalist represents a different approach that has been tested in the marketplace. The final winner in the challenge will be announced in April 2016 after the finalists have pursued their dissemination plans for a year and will get an additional $50,000.<br>\n<br>\nThe applicants for the challenge were given five directives, to improve quality, expand health care access while lowering delivery costs, demonstrating real value and the ability to scale to create broader impact. Harvard received over 500 applicants from 29 countries and 43 states for the Health Acceleration Challenge.<br>\n<br>\nOver 60% of the applications were from for-profit companies and 40% were from not-for-profit organizations. The applications were a mix of provider- and patient-facing innovations, clinical and operational solutions. Approximately 370 applications were focused on provider-facing innovations rather than directly addressing to patients. 38% of the provider-facing applications were aimed at innovation in hospital care, 14% in self-care, 10% on tele-medicine, 10% in physician offices, 8% in home health care and 20% in other medical settings.', '14443893451444389793.jpg', '', '', 0, 2, 0.75),
(127, '‘Logi Circle’ to monitor your homes remotely using your smartphones', '', 'Logitech has launched home monitoring system ‘Logi Circle’ that will help users supervise their homes via their smartphones. Logi Circle has a portable camera, which sends a high definition live feed of your home to your smartphone via an Android/iOS app. The portable camera has a 135-degree wide angle view and 8x zoom. It comes with a built-in battery that provides three hours of non-stop streaming.<br>\n<br>\nThe system supports the Logitech cloud service, which saves home feeds of 24 hours for free. Logitech Logi Circle allows you to view recordings via filters as well as display 30-second highlights of the previous day. It comes with Scene Intuition Technology that monitors a home owner’s routine and sends out alerts in case of any deviations. The unique camera is priced at US$200.<br>\n<br>\nThe home security market is expected to grow at a CAGR of 8.7% between 2015-2020 and reach $47,542.52 million by 2020. America is the biggest market for home security solutions while APAC and European markets are opening up to the sector.', '14446503681444650523.png', '', '', 0, 2, 0.5642857142857143),
(128, 'Helpost.com, world’s first local crowd sourced community', '', 'Of late, crowdsourcing has become one of the most innovative ways to launch or market new ideas. The platform helps in bringing startups and investors together and has also been used by companies as well as nonprofit organizations to develop ideas.<br>\n<br>\nGlobally, crowd funding helped raise US $6.1 billion in 2013 and grew over 167% to reach $16.2 billion in 2014. The industry is expected to double in 2015 to reach $34.4 billion.<br>\n<br>\nHelpost_V03Helpost.com is the world’s first local crowd sourced community where users can get information about local accommodation, interest groups, restaurants etc. on a single platform. The company has a strong presence in over 60 countries and has answered over 300,000 queries since its launch.<br>\n<br>\nHere is what Amol Goel, Founder of Helpost, have to say about the visionary startup. (Amol is an alumni of Nottingham Business School, and has worked with renowned international corporations like Audi UK Ltd., Nottingham Forest Football Club and Leo Burnett India before starting Helpost. He has been a startup development consultant and mentored over 50 startups.)<br>\n<br>\nHere are some excerpts from an interview with Amol Goel, Founder Helpost.<br>\n<br>\nQ: What led to the idea behind helpost?<br>\n<br>\nR: As a Marketing Consultant I had to travel extensively and faced problems in finding accommodation, electricians, plumbers, friends, interest groups, restaurants, etc. in different cities. The only tangible solution was to get information from the local people of that city.<br>\n<br>\nThis led to the creation of Helpost, an online ‘Prosocial- professional and social networking platform’ where you can find first hand information from the people around you. Helpost comes from a Finnish word ‘Helposti’, which means easily. Hence Helpost, to make things easy.<br>\n<br>\nQ: How does Helpost work?<br>\n<br>\n R: Users have to register on the website where they can offer their skills with the help of #hashtags. Employers can post jobs in a city with the relevant skills needed in the form of hashtags, and people with those hash tagged skills get an instant notification of the need being arisen. Users can also look directly for people or business in their vicinity by searching with the relevant hashtags and reach out to them via direct messages.<br>\n<br>\nQ: Since its inception, what has been the response / growth graph to date of the company?<br>\n<br>\nR: Helpost has chapters in over 60 cities in various countries and has a strong community of 2,50,000 members, 44,000 Twitter followers and 42000 Facebook followers. Every day we get 2,500 requests on Facebook and over 100 requests on Helpost.com. The website has seen a growth of 20% month to month in users and queries, and 6 times the responses to queries.<br>\n<br>\nQ: What is the innovative tech / marketing edge of Helpost against competitors?<br>\n<br>\n R: Helpost offers a more personal solution to every problem, shared peer to peer. There aren’t many people who provide the exact same method of reaching the solution to a problem, the way Helpost does.<br>\n<br>\nOther platforms like Google, Facebook, Justdial, Quora, Twitter etc., naturally connect people; however we don’t really see anyone as a direct competitor. Google tells you all the things available around you, but Helpost tells you the exact solution through people’s own experience. In the bigger picture we don’t really see a competition; instead we foresee collaborations with other social media sites for growth.<br>\n<br>\nQ: What is the company’s revenue generation model?<br>\n<br>\n R: We have multiple revenue streams in pipeline. First is our B2C platform where we charge businesses a nominal fee to verify and manage their accounts. Second is HELPAY, our unique help wallet where you earn money by helping people.<br>\n<br>\nQ. Any new campaigns / initiatives in the anvil or associated with to drive Helpost?<br>\n<br>\nR: We have run quite a few social activities where we try to engage masses through community building and social awareness. For example, we had recently run our campaign on smarter parking called the #PRINTPASTEPARK. It picked up a lot of traction with hundreds of shares and thousands of views. We have a very strong presence on all social media with a standalone E-Magazine called Helpost READ.<br>\n<br>\nQ: Some insights on the kind of segment Helpost is connected too and aims for and how it’s working towards it.<br>\n<br>\nR: Every digital user who is on social media or has the potential to get on to social media is our target group. We have narrowed down to 20 to 35 year old age group, as they are the main social media influencers.<br>\n<br>\nWe started off with the thought of catering to travelers or newbie’s in a city, but eventually we ended up creating strong city based communities where locals started asking for all sorts of help, from service, to opinion to information. With Helpost we want to make sure that there is not even a single person who is unable to get help at the right time. The platform will open so many new doors as well as opportunities for millions of rural people.<br>\n<br>\nQ: What is Helpost.com aiming for in the horizon of 5-10 years?<br>\n<br>\nR: Helpost plans to cover all Tier 1 cities in India by 2015 end. We plan to engage with 5 Million users in 10 countries, with 1 million registered businesses out of which premium businesses would be over 50,000. We have already started expanding to countries like Africa, and slowly by 2016 we will cover a few more countries in Asia. If we keep scaling at the current speed we will be one of the fastest growing startups by 2018.', '14446507131444650873.jpg', '', '', 0, 2, 0.4799498746867168),
(129, 'Artificial Intelligence startups on the rise', '', 'Artificial or machine learning companies are on the rise, with tech giants like Google, Microsoft, Apple and Facebook all investing in Artificial Intelligence Startups.<br><br>\nVC investment in AIArtificial Intelligence has attracted more than $17 billion in investments since 2009 and $2 billion was invested in 322 companies with Artificial Intelligence -like technology in 2014. Private investment in the Artificial Intelligence sector has been expanding at an average of 62 percent y-o-y for the last four years. In 2014, there has been a jump of 302% in funding for Artificial Intelligence startups.<div><br></div><div><span style="font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 15px; line-height: 26.25px;">Artificial Intelligence covers 5 segments: neuro computers, expert systems, autonomous robots, smart embedded systems and intelligent assistance systems.</span><br></div>', '14446511951444651395.png', '', '', 0, 2, 0.4740566037735849),
(130, '', '', '<p style="zoom: 1; border: 0px; font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 15px; margin-bottom: 1.625em; outline: 0px; padding: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; color: rgb(85, 85, 85); line-height: 26.25px;">Artificial Intelligence covers 5 segments: neuro computers, expert systems, autonomous robots, smart embedded systems and intelligent assistance systems. The industry is predicted to grow at&nbsp;<a href="http://www.bccresearch.com/market-research/instrumentation-and-sensors/smart-machines-market-ias094a.html" style="zoom: 1; border: 0px; font-family: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-weight: inherit; margin: 0px; outline: 0px; padding: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; color: black;">an average of 19.7% to reach US $15.3 billion by 2019</a>.</p><p style="zoom: 1; border: 0px; font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 15px; margin-bottom: 1.625em; outline: 0px; padding: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; color: rgb(85, 85, 85); line-height: 26.25px;">IBM has over 500 patents in Artificial Intelligence and has set aside $100 million for investments in Artificial Intelligence startups. Recently, Google acquired Artificial Intelligence Startup&nbsp;<a href="http://deepmind.com/" style="zoom: 1; border: 0px; font-family: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-weight: inherit; margin: 0px; outline: 0px; padding: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; color: black;">DeepMind</a>&nbsp;for $400 million, while world’s largest social network Facebook has its own dedicated&nbsp;<a href="https://research.facebook.com/ai" style="zoom: 1; border: 0px; font-family: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-weight: inherit; margin: 0px; outline: 0px; padding: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; color: black;">Artificial Intelligence research</a>laboratory. Tech giant&nbsp;<a href="http://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-10-05/apple-acquires-startup-developing-advanced-ai-for-phones" style="zoom: 1; border: 0px; font-family: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-weight: inherit; margin: 0px; outline: 0px; padding: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; color: black;">Apple acquired secretive deep learning startup Perceptio</a>&nbsp;for an undisclosed amount. Apart from these big names, smaller companies like MobileEye, Marketo and Nidec are also working on Artificial Intelligence technologies.</p><p style="zoom: 1; border: 0px; font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 15px; margin-bottom: 1.625em; outline: 0px; padding: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; color: rgb(85, 85, 85); line-height: 26.25px;">Many startups have jumped into the Artificial Intelligence bandwagon and have raised millions in funding.<a href="http://www.sentient.ai/" style="zoom: 1; border: 0px; font-family: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-weight: inherit; margin: 0px; outline: 0px; padding: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; color: black;">Sentient Technologies</a>&nbsp;which received $103.5 million in its Series C funding in late 2014 bringing the total funding to $143 million, has built the largest intelligent systems in existence.&nbsp;<a href="https://www.metamind.io/" style="zoom: 1; border: 0px; font-family: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-weight: inherit; margin: 0px; outline: 0px; padding: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; color: black;">Metamind</a>&nbsp;backed by Khosla ventures raised $8 million in funding; the company uses deep learning capabilities for image classification. Pune based&nbsp;<a href="http://www.hugefly.com/" style="zoom: 1; border: 0px; font-family: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-weight: inherit; margin: 0px; outline: 0px; padding: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; color: black;">Hugefly</a>&nbsp;has raised an undisclosed amount in funding, the company provides data analytics and pattern recognition techniques to companies.</p><p style="zoom: 1; border: 0px; font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 15px; margin-bottom: 1.625em; outline: 0px; padding: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; color: rgb(85, 85, 85); line-height: 26.25px;">Artificial Intelligence has wide applications in different industries including healthcare with personalized medicine, insurance, cyber crime and security, assisted living as well as e-commerce. Many e-commerce firms like Amazon, Flipkart etc., are already using deep machine learning and Artificial intelligence in areas like Product Recommendation, Intelligent Agent, Voice Powered Search, Visual Search and Image Recognition etc., for targeted marketing.</p><p style="zoom: 1; border: 0px; font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 15px; margin-bottom: 1.625em; outline: 0px; padding: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; color: rgb(85, 85, 85); line-height: 26.25px;">Artificial Intelligence is slated to become one of the most disruptive technologies in IT industry and is expected to see huge growth in the future. The industry is poised for a revolution in Artificial Intelligence technology, be it smart homes, smart devices, online shopping, driverless cars or virtual assistants.</p>', '14446512031444651522.png', '', '', 129, 3, 0.5773672055427251),
(131, 'Big Data, the latest buzzword for businesses !', '', 'Of late, Big Data has emerged as the latest buzzword for businesses looking to get that extra edge in the dynamic market. In fact, 89% business leaders across the globe believe that big data will revolutionize businesses pretty much the same way the internet did. This is evident from a Wikibon survey that suggests that the global Big data market is expected to cross the $ 84 billion revenue mark by 2026, up from $ 27.36 million in 2014, indicating an exponential growth<br>\n<br>\nGlobally across industries, Big Data is being adopted by the financial sector, followed by technology,telecommunications,retail and government sectors among others.<br>\n<br><br>\n48% of companies are using Big Data to understand customer behavior, 21% for operational analytics and 21% for fraud and compliance. Investments are pouring in Big Data from North America, followed by Europe, middle east and Africa. In the Asia/Pacific region Big Data investments have seen a major jump of 106% in the last 2 years. ', '14446515041444651759.png', '', '', 0, 2, 1.2945736434108528),
(132, '', '', '<p style="zoom: 1; border: 0px; font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 15px; margin-bottom: 1.625em; outline: 0px; padding: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; color: rgb(85, 85, 85); line-height: 26.25px;">uggernaut players like&nbsp;<a href="http://www.kdnuggets.com/2014/12/top-10-big-data-companies-revenue.html" style="zoom: 1; border: 0px; font-family: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-weight: inherit; margin: 0px; outline: 0px; padding: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; color: black;">IBM, HP, Dell, SAP, Oracle</a>&nbsp;etc. are investing millions in this particular domain and for all the right reasons. They are increasi<strong style="zoom: 1; border: 0px; font-family: inherit; font-style: inherit; margin: 0px; outline: 0px; padding: 0px; vertical-align: baseline;">ngly relying on the power of data to derive better cost and operational efficiency</strong>&nbsp;and take better decisions to boost their top-lines and bottom-lines,&nbsp; thereby giving them the an edge in the cut-throat market.</p><p style="zoom: 1; border: 0px; font-family: ''Open Sans'', sans-serif; font-size: 15px; margin-bottom: 1.625em; outline: 0px; padding: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; color: rgb(85, 85, 85); line-height: 26.25px;">Then there are companies like&nbsp;<a href="http://www.ambyint.com/" style="zoom: 1; border: 0px; font-family: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-weight: inherit; margin: 0px; outline: 0px; padding: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; color: black;">Ambyint</a>&nbsp;that are taking things a notch higher by combining the power of Internet of Things (IoT) and the business intelligence derived from raw data to offer ‘smart’ and disruptive technologies that can revolutionize the world.There’s a whole world out there waiting to be explored using big data, and this is just the beginning.</p>', '14446516861444651813.png', '', '', 131, 1, 0.39970717423133234),
(133, 'Indian origin researcher invents Foldascope-a folding paper microscope', '', 'Indian origin researcher, Manu Prakash, of Stanford University has invented a new folding paper microscope that costs less than a dollar to manufacture. The microscope dubbed ‘Foldascope’ is printed on a thick paper and can be assembled in origami-style in just a few minutes. Prakash states that the paper, lens and other parts of the microscope cost just 50 cents.<br>\n<br>\nLast year, Prakash and his team had distributed 10,000 Foldscopes to users willing to test them. Many users have been submitting their findings at the Foldscope site, from first-graders looking at banana seeds to investigating tiny insects and more.<br>\n<br>\nEntomologist and science reporter Aaron Pomerantz tested the foldascope in the Peruvian Amazon rainforest and stated in a post, “Long story short, this device is amazing”. He adds, “I was able to investigate tiny insects, mites, fungi and plant cells from 140X (magnification) to 480X.”<br>\n<br>\nPrakash says that Foldscope will be able to help health care workers detect blood-borne illnesses in the field. He stated in a Stanford blog post, “I wanted to make the best possible disease-detection instrument that we could almost distribute for free. What came out of this project is what we call use-and-throw microscopy.” Although the Foldacope is not commercially available yet, Prakash and has team state that they are “working hard to make the microscopes commercially available via a spinoff/startup.”', '14446527851444652899.jpg', '', '', 0, 2, 0.5619174434087882),
(134, 'Emerging markets provide an unparalleled opportunity for app developers', '', 'According to a report from App Annie, emerging markets like Indonesia, Brazil, India, and Mexico have seen a massive growth in downloads and revenue and provide an unparalleled opportunity for app developers. The report is based on market-level app store growth for iOS and Google Play stores.<br>\n<br>\nThe App Annie report reveals that in Q1, 2015; iOS is ahead of Google Play in revenue, however Google Play has seen more downloads. Google Play’s worldwide downloads were 70% higher than the iOS App Store in Q1,2015 and up from 60% in Q3 2014. The main drivers behind Google Play’s growth are emerging markets like Mexico, India, Russia, Indonesia and Brazil. The increase is attributed to first time smartphone users in the emerging countries and the launch of Google’s Android One initiative.<br>\n<br>\niOS App Store’s worldwide revenue was 70% higher than Google Play, up from about 60% in Q3 2014. iOS main revenue can be attributed from Apple’s core markets China and US. China has surpassed US in the number of downloads in Q1, 2015. The main reason for the increase in revenue was the launch of Apple’s flagship iPhone 6 and iPhone 6 Plus smartphones. Check out the complete report from App Annie.', '14446530401444653289.png', '', '', 0, 2, 0.4704724409448819),
(135, 'Innovative apps that are making our life easier', '', 'Companies are creating and launching new innovative apps/products every day. There are multiple apps for messaging, exercising, shopping etc. that have an impact on our daily lives. In this article we are discussing some innovative apps/tech that has made our lives much simpler.<br>\n<br>Taxi Apps<br>\n<br>\nTaxi apps like Uber/Ola have definitely made our life a lot easier. Want to catch a cab or late for a meeting just check in the app and get the nearest cab around in minutes. No more haggling for price or finding change, everything is online and deducted automatically from a linked credit card or bank account ensuring a hassle free experience.<br>\n<br>\nWearables/Fitness Apps<br>\n<br>\nFitness apps like Google Fit, Mi Fit keep a track of our fitness goals, while monitoring our daily activity level, sleep cycles etc. Ideal for fitness conscious people, the apps sends daily reminders and notifications to help achieve personal health goals and stay fit in our busy schedules.<br>\n<br>\nFood Tech<br>\n<br>\nFood tech has become a multi-million dollar industry with new ventures coming out every day. Food aggregator sites like Faasos, Tinyowl, Cyberchef, Biteclub etc. which offer a revolving menu, wider choices, have definitely made lives easier for bachelors and working couples.<br>\n<br>\nN-commerce<br>\n<br>\nN-commerce has become a big thing these days, apps like Lazylad, Peppertap, Grofers etc. make sure you get access to your everyday staples without any hassle. You can place orders for your everyday needs, like groceries via an online app and have them delivered at your doorstep in a pre-scheduled time saving time instead for things that you really love to do.', '14446533991444653565.png', '', '', 0, 2, 0.29136690647482016),
(136, 'Digital, Social and Mobile stats for India, 2015 by wearesocial.net', '', 'The We Are Social’s new Digital, Social and Mobile in 2015 report -data points explain the immense potential and market in India in the Digital, Social and Mobile arena that is yet to be tapped!<br>\n<br>\nThe report that has stats for 240+ countries and profiling 30 of the world’s biggest economies in detail is supposedly the most comprehensive, concise and free compendium of up-to-date digital statistics.<br>\n<br>\nSome highlights of the India centric data:<br>\n<br>\nTotal Population: 1265 M (urbanization 31%)<br>\nActive Internet Users: 243 M (penetration 19%)<br>\nActive Social Media Accounts: 118 M (penetration 9%)<br>\nMobile Connections: 946 M (vs. population 75%)<br>\nActive Mobile Social Accounts: 100M (penetration 8%)<br>\nPercentage of the mobile subscriptions that are broadband (3G &amp; 4G): 11%<br>\nPercentage of the population using social media apps on mobile: 10%<br>\nShare of the webpage views- mobile phone: 72%<br>\nShare of the webpage views – desktops and laptops: 27%<br>\nTop Active social platforms:  Whatsapp: 11%  ; Facebook Messenger: 9%; Facebook: 8% ; Skype: 8% ; Google+: 7% ; Twitter: 6% ; WECHAT: 5% ; LinkedIn: 5% ; Pinterest: 4% and Viber: 4%<br>\nAll the above data and many more in the report when analyzed carefully, lead to the understanding and clarity that mobile internet penetration is yet far from reality in India but very much an important and logical way to go for any marketer keeping the global trends in mind. The data also messages that it cannot be a completely either or approach. Digital India requires many infrastructural and localized –regional aspects to be taken into consideration and mobilization awareness at the ground level.', '14449879861444988259.jpg', '', '', 0, 3, 0.7507836990595611);
