(137, '‘The Travelling Boutique’ will make your trip memorable', '', 'The Travelling Boutique (TTB) is a one-stop shop for travelers and aims to provide a unique retail experience with merchandise that meets customers, every travel need. It offers a diverse range of products, for all travelers, whether you want to go for a business trip or a family vacation or just a trip with friends, TTB has something for you.<br>\n<br>\nThe Travelling Boutique, started in February 2015 by two friends Paran Sheth and Pooja Parikh. Since its launch TTB has already completed more than 100 retail and corporate orders. The company plans to diversify into children as well as luxury sectors in the next few months. Also expand and manufacture its own products.<br>\n<br>\nWith the massive growth in the Indian travel industry, TTP has a huge potential. According to a recent report, the travel and tourism sector will contribute Rs. 8.22 trillion to GDP and 37.4 million jobs by 2015 end. The growth is driven by visa reforms, and infrastructure improvements under the new government. More and more travelers are utilizing budget deals, airfare sales etc. to travel.<br>\n<br>\nThe company says, “Our aim is to find and give a traveler everything he/she would need to make their travels smooth. That’s where our journey began to become a holistic market place that covers brands, price points and categories of travel accessories that any globetrotter would require. Not quite there yet, but definitely on our way! We want to be every traveler’s online travel accessory store”.', '14449882941444988659.png', '', '', 0, 1, 0.5885714285714285),
(138, 'Lasers a danger to self drive cars', '', 'Security researchers have warned that a modified, low-cost laser could create ghost like objects in the path of autonomous cars, making them slow down and stop completely.<br>\n<br>\nJonathan Petit, principal scientist at software company Security Innovation, demonstrated that by using a simple laser pen and a pulse generator, anyone could create phantom objects like cars, buildings, people etc. and stop the self driven cars. The homemade device costs just $40 to make.<br>\n<br>\nSelf-driving vehicles come with a LIDAR (Light Detection and Ranging) system to detect potential roadblocks. These LADAR systems use lasers, mounted on top of the cars to detect what’s nearby. Researchers state that by sending false data to the system, anyone can confuse the cars and stop them. Dr Petit says that this type of vulnerability should be a sort of wake-up call to self-driving car makers.<br>\n<br>\n“If a self-driving car has poor inputs, it will make poor driving decisions. I can spoof thousands of objects and basically carry out a denial of service attack on the tracking system so it’s not able to track real objects.” Dr Petit told IEEE Spectrum. “I can take echoes of a fake car and put them at any location I want,” he added.<br>\n<br>\nJonathan Petit had written the paper while he was a research fellow at the University of Cork’s computer security group. He will be presenting the findings at the upcoming Black Hat Europe conference in November.', '14449885051444988933.jpg', '', '', 0, 1, 0.6655737704918033),
(140, 'Indian Retail market to see major restructuring', '', 'The Indian retail market is estimated to be a $350 billion market and grocery accounts for over 70% of the total. Online sales in FMCG and grocery are expected to account for 5% of total sales by 2020. In the last 18 months over 100 food grocery startups have launched in the country and nearly 80% have raised funds.<br>\n<br>\nBigBasket has emerged as one of the biggest players in the online food and grocery space. The Bangalore based company has raised over $50 million in a Series C funding. It has over 5,00,000 customers across 27 cities in India and services nearly 20000 orders a day. The company is looking for major expansion in Tier 2 cities and has earmarked nearly Rs 100 Crore for marketing in 2015-2016.<br>\n<br>\nGurgaon based Peppertap has raised $36 million in funding led by Snapdeal and has raised over $47 million till date. It is on the verge of closing another $20 million funding in the next few weeks, according to its founder. The company operates in over 18 cities and services nearly 25000 plus orders a day. Peppertap plans to expand to 75 cities across India by year end. The company is planning to invest in technology and supply chain to improve its services over the next few months.<br>\n<br>\nHyperlocal service Grofers has raised over $45 million from existing investors Tiger Global and Sequoia Capital. It operates in 25 cities and gets 30,000 orders a day. Grofers delivers groceries, bakery items, fresh fruits &amp; vegetables, personal care and baby care products and much more via its app and promises delivery in just 90 minutes. The company is expanding aggressively and is currently in talks with SoftBank to raise another $100 million in funding.<br>\n<br>\nMumbai based LocalBanya raised over $20 million in funding in 2014. The company has currently stopped taking orders on its website as has stated that it is currently upgrading its technology and service. According to reports LocalBanya is planning to raise another $35-40 million by the end of the fiscal year.<br>\n<br>\nThe Indian online retail industry is still in the nascent stage and is expected to grow 20%-30% annually. However, startups in this space are operating at a margin of just 10%-15% and providing huge discounts in order to acquire customers. The Indian Retail market will see a major restructuring and consolidation in the next couple of years.', '14449888341444989223.png', '', '', 0, 2, 0.9154228855721394),
(141, 'Food Tech startups rake in big money', '', 'Estimated as a $50 billion market, with 16% y-o-y growth the food tech industry is touted to be the next big thing. Globally, a total of over $1.2 billion has been invested across multiple deals in the food tech space.<br>\n<br>\nNew food-restaurant aggregator sites, food search and discovery platforms as well as companies targeting the segment -food logistics are cropping up globally. The food -tech sites are a boon for the young working generation who don’t have the time to cook or go shopping for their food every day and prefer to enjoy multiple cuisines while sitting at home or at their office.<br>\n<br>\nUS based food tech companies Sprig, SpoonRocket, Munchery, Blue Apron and Plated have seen amazing success in the last few years. US based Munchery has an estimated valuation of $180 million, while Blue Apron is valued at over $500 million. Just Eat an online search and delivery food platform is valued at $2.44 billion.<br>\n<br>\nIn India, the food tech industry is still at a nascent stage and is expected to grow 15 times the current market size. The food business is estimated to be worth $48 billion, while food delivery is valued at $15 billion. Some of the major players in the restaurant search and discovery are Zomato and FoodPanda, which have over 1 Lakh restaurants listed on their platform. Zomato has raised a total of $225 million funding and Foodpanda has raised over $310 million from investors.<br>\n<br>\nFood aggregator sites Faasos, Yumist, Spoonjoy, Swiggy and TinyOwl have also received substantial VC funding. Faasos has raised over $20 million in funding, Swiggy has received a funding of $16.5 million, while TinyOwl and Yumist have each raised $1 million in funding.<br>\n<br>\nThe food tech industry is expected to grow exponentially over the next few years. However, with so many startups coming up in the space, there is an increased competition with companies giving more discounts and cutting prices for customer acquisition. Believe, over the next year, the food tech industry is expected to see a lot of consolidation and churning. Startups will need the right mix of creativity, innovation and business acumen to sustain and be profitable in the long run.', '14449890411444989433.jpg', '', '', 0, 3, 0.6612903225806451),
(142, 'HP unveils myriad of gaming-specific computing products', '', 'Hewlett Packard, the technology focused American giant has announced a dozen PC products specifically meant for hardcore gamers. This follows post the news of the company’s future split [HP will be segregated into 2 different companies come November] which will directly coincide with its nascent partnership program.<br>\n<br>\nHP Unveils a Myriad of Gaming-Specific Computing ProductsUsing the cutting edge most updated chips from Intel and MS Windows 10, these new highly awaited HP products include the likes of a gaming notebook and high premium PCs.<br>\n<br>\n“Serious gamers want high-end performance that delivers truly amazing experiences in a package with edgy designs but at a price point that does not break the bank,” said Kevin Frost who is the general manager of consumer personal systems in a press release.<br>\n<br>\nBoasting a 15.6-inch screen, the new and improved HP Pavilion Gaming notebook comes equipped with graphics chips from Nvidia Corp. It is valued at $899.99. Via Windows 10, users can now get first hand access to the Game Streaming option present in the Xbox application which will allow them to bask in the glory of their Xbox One games on their HP Pavilion Gaming notebook anytime-anywhere in their homes as reported in bizjournals.com', '14449892091444989359.png', '', '', 0, 2, 0.38954869358669836),
(143, 'India’s rise as a startup and investors destination!', '', 'India’s rise as a startup and investor destination in 2014-2015 and the continued momentum in 2015-16, is primarily due to the increased interest from investors and a wave of entrepreneurship all across. One of the biggest investments is from Taiwan’s Foxconn which has committed to invest $5 billion to set up R&amp;D and manufacturing plants over the next five years in the country. Global smartphone manufacturers like Samsung, Gionee and Xiaomi are setting up their manufacturing plants in the country. Apart from these many international players like GM, Siemens, First Solar etc, have sent proposals worth US $ 16.56 billion in the last year to the government to set up their manufacturing plants in the country. These new ventures will bring opportunities of employment too in the country. For example, the Foxconn’s project which is stated to provide 1 million jobs in India by 2020.To further improve employment opportunities, Google and PayTM have partnered with IAMAI and have launched the Mobile 10X program. Under this initiative the companies will partner to set up centers all across India and provide training to over 5,00,000 mobile app developers in the next five years.<br>\n<br>\nIn the first half of 2015 India received over $31 billion in foreign investment, scoring over countries like China and US. India saw $3 billion more investments than China, which received $28 billion in FDI and over $4 billion more than the US which has $27 billion FDI in the first half of 2015. UNCTAD’s World Investment Report 2015, states that FDI investments have surged 22% in the country during 2014, taking India to the 9th spot globally.<br>\n<br>\nThe positivity and rise in sentiments to an extent is also the resultant of the recent announcements by the Government’s such as: relaxed investment norms and promised infrastructure developments encouraging foreign investors along with launch of initiatives like ‘Digital India’ and ‘Make in India’. Added to all, the recently announced report by NASSCOM, which states India to be the fastest growing and third largest start-up ecosystem in the world after the U.S. and the U.K and total no of startup to grow from 3,100 to 11,500 by the end of 2020 can also be looked at as a key reason for adding up to increased investor interest. India having emerged as the fastest growing startup ecosystem is reported to have received over $3.5 billion in investments in the first half of 2015, which is double of last year.<br>\n<br>\nInternational players are also looking at investing in startups; recently global giant Qualcomm has announced a $150 million venture capital fund for Indian startup companies. Overall, India received over $1.9 billion venture capital funds and $5.1 billion in private equity funds in the first half of 2015. Initiatives like Nasscom’s 10,000 startups are playing a role of catalysts and in mentoring of  startups to scale up with the setting up of warehouses.<br>\n<br>\nAll these factors have for sure accelerated the pace of growth of the startup ecosystem in the country. The country has seen an improvement in world indexes like the Global Competitiveness Index compiled by World Economic Forum, where it has jumped 16 places to reach the 55th spot, ending its five year decline. Other emerging countries have either seen a decline or stagnation in the report. China, one of the biggest competitive economies is in 28th place, same as last year due to global economic slowdown. Bangalore has emerged as one of the fastest moving start-up cities globally, according to the latest Startup Genome report.', '14449893691444989756.gif', '', '', 0, 1, 0.9485148514851485),
(144, 'Bitcoin, gaining traction globally', '', 'Bitcoin is said to become a mainstream digital currency for doing financial transactions, globally. The Global Bitcoin Technology Market is estimated to grow at a CAGR of 7.26% in the next five years. Bitcoin surpasses the need for intermediaries or third parties while making financial transactions, leading to lesser transaction fees as well as multi-mode payment methods to users. The block chain technology allows users to record and make secure transactions on an instantaneous basis, replacing the more costly and tedious processes.<br>\n<br>\nBy the end of this financial year mobile banking users will exceed 1 billion, leading to many banks and financial institutes turning to Bitcoin technology for secure transactions. Some of the foremost names in the financial sector have invested $30 million in Chain Inc, Including NASDAQ Inc, Citi Ventures, Visa, Capital One Financial Corp., Orange SA and Fiserv Inc.<br>\n<br>\nIndia is forecasted to become one of the largest Bitcoin markets; however the bitcoin revolution is still in the nascent stage in the country. Bangalore based Unocoin is one of the first bitcoin companies in India. The company has 3000 registered users and claims that 150,000 wallets have been downloaded. Zebpay is another prominent startup, which offers a mobile bitcon wallet to make transactions via mobile numbers. The Ahmedabad based startup has raised $2 million in a second round of funding earlier this year. The company has over 2000 users in India.<br>\n<br>\nPopular bitcoin wallet and exchange Coinbase is also eyeing operations in India. The company already offers its services in 26 countries globally and plans to expand to 40 countries soon. However, the lack of knowledge has been hindering adoption of the technology in India. RBI has been slow to adapt bitcoin and has also warned about the danger of cyber threat with the tech. It is expected that as more and more startups and new technology comes up, awareness will be created and more users will start adopting Bitcoin in India', '14449894451444989589.jpg', '', '', 0, 2, 0.5615384615384615),
(145, 'Retail giants and ecommerce, betting big time on Indian market', '', 'Global e-commerce sales are expected to reach $3.5 trillion over the next five years and internet will account for 7.3% of all global retail sales this year. By 2019 online sales are expected to double and reach $3.551 trillion, or 12.4% of total retail sales of $28.550 trillion.<br>\n<br>\nAsia-Pacific market is growing faster than any other global market at a rate of 35.2% year over year and is estimated to have $875 billion in online sales in 2015. The Indian e-commerce market which is just 1% of China is expected to expand to $16 billion by 2016 providing a huge opportunity to vendors.<br>\n<br>\nRetail giants and ecommerce ‘biggies’ are betting big time on Indian market such as Walmart announcing its plans to spend $2 Billion over the next two years in e-commerce, to compete with Amazon Inc. The company has also revealed its plans to open 500 retail stores over the next five years and establish its online presence in India.  Amazon India which entered the Indian market in 2013, crossed the $2 billion sales mark in the country in less than 2 years after it started its operations. Flipkart is aiming for $5 billion in sales by the end of March 2016, while Snapdeal is expected to reach $3 billion in online sales by March next year. Flipkart owned Myntra plans to sell goods worth $1 billion by March 2016.<br>\n<br>\nChina’s largest e-commerce company, Alibaba.com has pledged an investment of $10-billion in India over the next few years. Apart from global players industry leaders like Azim Premji and Ratan Tata are also investing in e-commerce companies.<br>\n<br>\nIndia e-commerce market has a lot of potential for growth as more consumers shift to smartphones. Online shoppers are expected to increase to 100 million in 2016 and over 200 million new customers are expected to switch to e-commerce over the next two years as smartphone penetration increases in the country. Over 50 million shoppers are expected to be added from Tier 1 and Tier 2 cities. With more and more people shifting to online buying there is a huge opportunity for retailers as well as e-commerce companies.', '14449898721444990370.png', '', '', 0, 1, 0.6854838709677419),
(146, 'India joins SKA – a 10 nation team, to design the world’s largest radio telescope', '', 'Another feather in the cap of Indian scientists – India now formally joins the Square Kilometre Array (SKA) project to design the world’s largest radio telescope.<br>\n<br>\nNot only will SKA be the largest, but will also be the most sensitive and fastest telescope in the world. It is not a single telescope, but an array of multiple antennas spread over thousands of kilometers across two continents – Australia and South Africa. It will be tens of times more sensitive and hundreds of times faster at mapping the sky, against any other facility of present times.<br>\n<br>\nThe SKA will combine signals from thousands of small antennas of two types: Parabolic antenna that can receive low frequency signals and dipole antenna that can receive high frequency signals. Together these antennas will simulate a single, highly sensitive, mammoth radio telescope.<br>\n<br>\nAccording to the website of the SKA, this project is designed to answer fundamental questions of science and about the laws of nature, such as: how did the Universe, and the stars and galaxies contained in it, form and evolve? Was Einstein’s theory of relativity correct? What is the nature of ‘dark matter’ and ‘dark energy’? What is the origin of cosmic magnetism? Is there life somewhere else in the Universe?<br>\n<br>\nIndia has been involved in SKA since many years, but on Monday, 5th October 2015, R.K.Sinha, the secretary of the Indian Department of Atomic Energy (DAE), formally joined 9 other nations by signing the documents on behalf of the Government of India, in the presence of Professor Philip Diamond, Director General of the SKA Project. The event was held in Mumbai and was marked by the presence of dignitaries from SKA – UK, scientists and officials from the DAE (and DST) and scientists from various research organizations in India.<br>\n<br>\nThe National Centre for Radio Astrophysics (NCRA-TIFR) in Pune will be the nodal institute for overseeing SKA related activities within India.<br>\n<br>\nLed by UK based SKA Organization (SKAO), this project has participation from Australia, Canada, China, Italy, the Netherlands, New Zealand, South Africa, and Sweden. Construction of Phase 1 is scheduled from 2018 to 2023, and early operations are to begin in 2020.<br>\n<br>\nProf. Yashwant Gupta of NCRA, Principal Investigator for the SKA related effort in India, said “At present, Indian scientists are leading one of the ten design work packages for the SKA, the Telescope Manager, which will be the brain and nervous system controlling the entire SKA observatory.', '14452324871445232730.jpg', '', '', 0, 2, 0.5628865979381443),
(147, 'IISc. students design Eco-friendly helicopter, win coveted International Award', '', 'Team Lakshya, comprising of four students from Indian Institute of Science (IIsc.), Bangalore designed an innovative four-blade small helicopter (a quad-rotor) that derives power from the vibrations of its blades. The team won the prestigious ‘Best New Entry – Graduate’ award at the Student Design Competition conducted by the American Helicopter Society International in association with other major helicopter companies<br>\n<br>\nIISc. brought glory to India the very first time it participated in this tough competition being held in US since the last 32 years. Needless to mention that the team was pitched against prominent colleges of America. Various academic as well as industry experts are on the Jury to judge this competition. The difficult specifications of the challenge were:<br>\n<br>\nTo design a small helicopter that could be used in urban settings to deliver packages as heavy as 10 kgs<br>\nThe helicopter should be Eco-friendly, both in terms of environment and noise pollution, hence (i) it should function with minimal carbon foot print, and (ii) the noise level should be lower than the prescribed limit<br>\nTeam Lakshya met this challenge by using a technology that partly powered their quad-rotor with the energy extracted from the oscillations of its own blades, leaving a lower carbon footprint even when compared to those powered only by fossil fuels. Rajnish Mallick, the team leader said, “It is indeed a proud moment and a wonderful experience to be recognized by the world’s most renowned vertical flight society,”<br>\n<br>\nWhat is interesting is that this technology is developed by IISc.’s Non Linear Multi functional Composites Analysis and Design (NMCAD) Laboratory of the Aerospace Department. IISc is in the process of patenting this technology. In June 2015, the team that developed this technology won the championship in Hamburg, Germany at the UNESCO–Airbus biennial innovation challenge, “Fly Your Ideas (FYI)”.', '14452326631445232786.jpg', '', '', 0, 2, 0.5895953757225434),
